The project started in xxxx with completion originally scheduled for yyyy. Minor delays pushed the anticipated go live date to zzzzz.
Compass is a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smart_card Smart Card]] based payment system, requiring users to pre purchase a card at one of the <booths> located at <skytrain and ???> and fill this card with credit. The <booths> support cash, credit, or debit.

About Us
About Trans-Fast Since 1988, Trans-Fast has provided its customers a reliable and affordable way of sending money to their families and friends. Our mission is to provide the most secure, fast, affordable and convenient way of sending money worldwide, anytime of the day or night. In addition to an extensive and ever growing network of agents in the U.S. and around the world, we have established an online presence. Our agent network, built over the last two decades, includes over a hundred thousand points of payment around the world.
With Trans-Fast your loved ones back home have choices, they can pick-up their remittance in cash, receive it directly into their bank account, and receive money via many other convenient options.
Having operated as a licensed money transfer company in the United States for over two decades, Trans-Fast adheres to the highest compliance and safety standards. In our 22 years in the money transfer business our customers have trusted and relied upon us to provide a high quality service.
We understand how important each and every transfer is to our customers and are committed to earning your business. We are expanding our online services to a growing list of countries, so please check back again if your country of choice is not yet offered.
Learn more about how to transfer money worldwide with Trans-Fast or refer to our Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ).
Questions, notifications, requests for refunds or further information can be sent to Trans-Fast, as follows: online, by telephone at 1-888-973-6383; or by mail at Trans-Fast Remittance LLC, attn: Customer Service, 44 Wall Street, Ste. 400, New York, NY 10005, USA.
For general information feel free to contact us.

{{Infobox Radio Station | image = | name = WKKD| frequency = 1580 [[AM radio|AM]] ([[kilohertz|kHz]])| city = [[Aurora, Illinois]]| airdate = 1960| area = | format = | owner = | facility_id = | power = 170 [[watt]]s day
200 watts night| erp = | haat = | branding = | slogan = | class = | former_callsigns = WKKD, WFVR| webcast = | website = | callsign_meaning = '''W'''ill, '''K'''ane, '''K'''endall and '''D'''uPage| sister_stations = | }} '''WKKD''' 1580 [[AM broadcasting|AM]] was a [[radio station]] licensed to [[Aurora, Illinois]]. The station began broadcasting in 1960 and initially ran 250 watts during daytime hours only with a directional pattern towards Aurora.Ghrist, John R. "Valley Voices: A Radio History" 1996. (p. 106) The station began simulcasting on 95.9 [[WERV-FM|WKKD-FM]] in 1961. The stations initially aired a [[Full service (radio format)|full service]] format that focused heavily on [[Country music]],[http://books.google.com/books?id=CiEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&dq=WKKD+Aurora&as_pt=MAGAZINES&cd=1#v=onepage&q=WKKD%20Aurora&f=false Folk Talent & Tunes] Sachs, Bill. (p. 8) Billboard. July 10, 1961. Accessed January 2, 2014[http://books.google.com/books?id=fR8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38&dq=WKKD+Aurora&as_pt=MAGAZINES&cd=5#v=onepage&q=WKKD%20Aurora&f=false Folk Talent & Tunes] Sachs, Bill. (p. 38) Billboard. July 18, 1960. Accessed January 2, 2014[http://books.google.com/books?id=uB8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA47&dq=WKKD+Aurora&lr=&as_pt=MAGAZINES&cd=13#v=onepage&q=WKKD%20Aurora&f=false Folk Talent & Tunes] Sachs, Bill. (p. 47) Billboard. May 16, 1960. Accessed January 2, 2014[http://books.google.com/books?id=ew8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=WKKD+Aurora&as_pt=MAGAZINES&cd=6#v=onepage&q=WKKD%20Aurora&f=false Nashville Scene] Whisenhunt, Elton. (p. 50) Billboard. February 5, 1966. Accessed January 2, 2014 By the early 1970s the simulcast had ended with WKKD-FM adopting a [[Beautiful music]] format. AM 1580's callsign was changed to WFVR, and it continued to air the country music format. WFVR's format was later changed to [[Adult Contemporary]]-[[Middle of the road (music)|MOR]].[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Station-Albums/Chicago-Trib-1979-Mar-About-Chi-Radio.pdf Stations, everywhere: a listeners' guide to the AM and FM bands] ''Chicago Tribune Magazine''. March 4, 1979. Accessed January 2, 2014 In the early 1980s the station's callsign was changed back to WKKD and it again simulcast WKKD-FM. In the mid '80s the station began broadcasting during nightime hours. By the late 80s the simulcast had ended, and WKKD AM had begun airing an [[oldies]] format.[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-1989-Fall.pdf WKKD AM 1580] Radio Chicago. Fall 1989. (p. 18) Accessed January 2, 2014[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-02-25/features/9001170010_1_beasley-broadcast-group-format-big-band-station Radio In Du Page] Wilhelmson, Brenda. ''Chicago Tribune.'' February 25, 1990. Accessed January 2, 2014 In the early 1990s WKKD-FM began simulcasting the oldies format of WKKD AM, and the stations became known as "Pure Gold 96"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-02-12/entertainment/9303180714_1_irish-rovers-concert-pure-gold Lettermen Bring Valentine Spirit To Norris] Todorovich, Lisa. ''Chicago Tribune.'' February 12, 1993. Accessed January 2, 2014 In March 1995, 1580 left the simulcast and began airing the [[Real Country]] [[country music]] format.[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-03-26/features/9503260089_1_fm-oldies-station-music-director-and-assistant Reporters Have New Assignments On Ch. 2 Mission] Nidetz, Steve. ''Chicago Tribune''. March 26, 1995. Accessed January 2, 2014 On July 1, 1996, the station adopted a [[Spanish language]] [[Tejano music]] format as "Viva 1580".[http://web.archive.org/web/19970414123243/http://www.wkkd.com/new.htm What's New @ WKKD Salter Broadcasting] wkkd.com. Internet Archive. April 14, 1997. Accessed January 2, 2014[http://web.archive.org/web/19970414123147/http://www.wkkd.com/1580.htm VIVA 1580 HOT TEJANO RADIO] wkkd.com. Internet Archive. April 14, 1997. Accessed January 2, 2014 In 1997, the station's format changed to [[CNN Headline News]].[http://web.archive.org/web/19971010013308/http://www.wkkd.com/1580am/index.html WKKD AM 1580] wkkd.com. Internet Archive. October 10, 1997. Accessed January 2, 2014 On January 1, 2002, the station was sold to Kovas Communications, and it began simulcasting the ethnic programming of [[WCGO|WONX]].[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-0EFF0020A5EB18D8.html WKKD sold to Kovas Broadcasting] The Beacon News. October 7, 2001. Accessed January 2, 2014 On January 31, 2005, the station adopted a "Health Radio" format, airing talk shows related to health, wellness and fitness.Feder, Robert. "Station goes full time as 'Health Radio' outlet". ''Chicago Sun Times''. January 27, 2005 This format would later be simulcast on 1600 [[WMCW]]. In 2007, Kovas Communications applied with the FCC to move WKKD to [[Silvis, Illinois]].[http://qconline.com/archives/qco/print_display.php?id=367017 Health Radio files for move to Silvis] ''Quad Cities Dispatch Argus''. December 18, 2007. Accessed January 2, 2014 In February 2008, the station was granted a construction permit to move WKKD to [[Silvis, Illinois]], and increase its power to 1,000 watts during the day and 1,400 watts at night.[http://qctimes.com/business/chicago-radio-station-may-move-to-silvis/article_d7b9dce8-64f9-5cb4-8bd1-d3c6068beceb.html Chicago radio station may move to Silvis] Burke, David. ''Quad City Business Journal''. February 25, 2008. Accessed January 2, 2014 In 2009, the station was taken off the air and Kovas Communications surrendered the station's license to the FCC.[http://ndb.at.ua/_ld/0/18_may_june09_enc.pdf Call Letter Changes] ''Medium Wave News''. May/June 2009. (p. 11) Accessed January 2, 2014 ==References== {{reflist}} {{Chicago Radio}} [[Category:Defunct radio stations in the United States]] [[Category:Radio stations established in 1960]] [[Category:Radio stations disestablished in 2009]] [[Category:Radio stations in Illinois|KKD]]
